==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Saxon [[unnan]], Old High German [[unnan]], Middle Dutch [[onnen]], Old Norse [[unna]] (Icelandic, Norwegian, Swedish [[unna]], Danish [[unde]]).

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'ʊnnan/}}

===Verb===
'''unnan''' (preterite-present: '''ann'''/'''onn''' ‘he grants’; *'''anst''' ‘you grant’; '''unnon''' ‘they grant’; {{Unicode|'''ūþe'''}} ‘he granted’)
# to [[grant]] or [[bestow]] (+ ''dat'' (person) + ''gen'' (thing))
# to [[intercede]]

